About this item

  • 1. No Neutral Wire Required Easily installed without rewiring your existing wire with single live wire design; Fire-retardant material and no electric arc new technology to guarantee secure and reliable working, giving the best look to blend with any wall design.
  • 2. Wide Range of Applications Work with minimum wattage 7W, Up to 800W for incandescent and 200W for LED/halogen.
  • 3.No Capacitance & No Hub Requierd Differ in features from traditional single live wire switch. This smart switch is featured as no capacitor installation required for normal and stable use, no more worry about the noise sound from the capacitor for better user experience.
  • 4.Control from anywhere Allows the switch to be controlled via Smart Life, touch control and voice
  • 5.Advantages & Note No neutral wire required/No capacitor required/No hub required/single pole; Only supports 2.4G network; Minimum control 7 watts. After the wiring is completed, you need to power on for 2-3 minutes before using the product for the first time.

Product Description

MoesGo Single Wire Smart Switch

Enjoy your Smart Life with MoesGo Products.

MoesGo WiFi Smart Push Button Switch WiFi Wireless Remote Control Single Live Wire Design and No Neutral Wire needed.This brand-new switch does not require capacitors and can directly replace traditional switches, which greatly facilitates the installation and wiring of users, allowing you to easily enjoy smart life.

Package List:

Smart switch*1(with panel)

Wire connectors*5

Screws*2

Wire label

Parameters:

  • Input Power:100~120V AC 60Hz
  • Control:Relay
  • Communication:WiFi 802.11 b/g/n 2.4GHz
  • Max Current:10A
  • Standby Power:0.5W
  • Button Life:50K times
  • Dimension:105*45*42.5 mm

Simple InstallationNo Neutral Wire Required No Capacitor Required No Hub Required

Installation Note

  • This is a single pole smart switch with no neutral wire (Suitable for 2-wire power supply environment), DO NOT use it as a 3 way switch
  • After completing the installation, the product needs to be charged for 5~7 minutes after the power is turned on for the switch initialization.
  • The light(s) will light up or flicker during the charging process, this is normal, the light(s) will automatically turn off after the charging is completed, the switch will start to work normally
  • Ensure the bulb(s) power meet the requirement of this switch to avoid bulb flickers or other abnormalitiesMinimum Wattage: 7W
  • Please make sure that the light is completely off then connecting to the Internet
  • Note: For more installation questions, please chech attached list "Installation Guide".

Note: Check whether the actual power of the bulb is too low(7w),the actual power of some irregular bulbs will be less than the nominal rated power.

How customer reviews and ratings work

Customer Reviews, including Product Star Ratings help customers to learn more about the product and decide whether it is the right product for them.

To calculate the overall star rating and percentage breakdown by star, we dont use a simple average. Instead, our system considers things like how recent a review is and if the reviewer bought the item on Amazon. It also analyzed reviews to verify trustworthiness.

Customers say

Customers find the smart light switch works well with Alexa and appreciate that it doesn't require a neutral wire. The build quality is good, particularly for older homes, and installation experiences are mixed - while some find it easy to install and setup, others describe it as frustrating to set up. Moreover, connectivity issues are common, with customers reporting frequent disconnections. Additionally, the switch receives mixed feedback about its functionality, with some reporting it stops working completely after 6 months.

4.5 stars, great right out of the box
I would give it 4.5 stars. Drawback is that the switchs back is thicker than a standard plug/switch so it makes my cover plate bulge a little. No one will notice it but me. See photo.Make sure you know which line in your wall is line and which is load. After that, hooking this up is easy and quick. Instructions provided are well written. After you let it sit 10 minutes before trying to configure it, youll probably have to reset it. Just hold the switch down/off for 5 seconds per the instructions, then follow the app instructions.Ill update this if warranted but right out of the box 15 minutes ago, its working well and integrated with Alexa.Update 1/10/23: I had some difficulties getting it to stay connected to my wifi. I contacted the seller and they ultimately replaced the switch with a new one and its been working great. Customer service response was very timely and thorough. I would happily buy another one of these. If you have issues, contact the seller.

  • Mark Wintle
    4.0 out of 5 stars The only choice for a wall switch when you have no C-wire
    Reviewed in the United States on July 12, 2023
    Verified Purchase
    Like most people, I have a wall bedroom switch that controls a dual socket. I split the wall plate so that the top socket is always powered and the bottom one is controlled by the wall-switch.

    Unfortunately, it used to be very common (unintentional pun) to just run only one wire to the wall switch to turn a socket on or off. When a regular smart switch turns off the lights, it also cuts power to itself. Without that power, theres no way for a smart switch to to run the electronics so it can always be listening for a command to turn the light back on. So Alexa can turn the light off just fine, but doesnt have any way to tell the dead smart switch to turn back on. Frustrating.

    If your switch box has a C-wire, then the smart switch will always be powered, so it can listen for on and off commands. Most of my switches have the C-Wire, so smartswitches and smart dimmers were simple to install all over the place. Unfortunately the construction people didnt do the right thing for the bedroom and foyer lights.

    The old solution to this annoyance was bit of a workaround. You buy a capacitor (its like a rechargeable battery) and wire it into the smart switch, so it can run its electronics using that charge until someone switches the light on again. When the switch is turned back on, the capacitor will recharge in a few seconds.

    Adding a capacitor to the smartswitch was minor surgery that required soldering, not to mention taking up room in a cramped box. Not great, plus time consuming and the result could be a bit delicate. Pretty much a hack.

    Luckily Moesgo made a switch that has a capacitor already built into it. No more surgery and soldering. Weirdly, its the only one I know of on the market.

    The Moesgo switch installs the same as most smartswitches. The only diffence you might notice is that once its installed it takes a couple seconds to charge the capacitor, but then its all ready to pair with your smarthome like most other switches.

    Sounds perfect, right? Imperfections:

    - if you dont have anything plugged into the outlet controlled by this switch, it will never get a chance to charge and the capacitor will run out. This wouldnt be the end of the world, except the switch wont even work manually once the electronics are out of juice. Plug a lamp back into the socket and it will be able to charge again. Sounds like no big deal, but until I figured this out, I was baffled why the switch was no longer reachable by Smartlife/Alexa.

    - I had a lot problems pairing to the switch, and so have others. One of my switches (the foyer) was effortless. The other was a nightmare of hours of troubleshooting until it just started working for no good reason.

    So, I recommend this smartswitch as the only simple way I know of to deal with a wall box that was oringially installed by the builder without a common (c-wire).

    PS: splitting a dual socket is a stupidly simple secret procedure that anyone can do with any socket (look it up). It amazes me how many people suffer with a wall switch that they cant use because it will turn off something like a TV when you really want to be able to switch the nightstands, and, obviously, dont want the TV to turn off as well when you flip the switch to turn off your bedside lamps. Having the socket split this way should be the default, and bonding them together should be the optional configuration. But its not, so you have to use YouTube to learn the simple secret to getting the use of your wall switch (dumb or smart) back.

  • trustnone
    3.0 out of 5 stars This is a great product for an older home w/o a neutral wire
    Reviewed in the United States on February 28, 2024
    Verified Purchase
    This is a great product for an older home. Our wiring loops to the light fist, then down to the switch.
    Which make using most smart switches unusable because there is no true neutral wire. New wiring goes from the switch to the light fixture which still maintains a true neutral wire @ the switch, which in turn actually allows a single pole switch to function as a true disconnect, and not a circuit interruptor, still leaving power at the light fixture.
    We have several smart switches in our home but only where we have an actual neutral wire. This switch allows you to use it with out a neutral wire.
    For some unknown reason we were only able to get intermittent wifi signal to this switch. Its less than 10 feet from our powerful router. It would work sometimes, & go (off line) about 50% or more of the time. Maybe we have a gremlin in our wiring IDK, but this did not work for us. It may however work fine for someone else. It turns out I actually have an active neutral wire in this box that I did not know was there.
    I replaced this switch with a Treatlife brand single pole switch which is the brand we are using elsewhere in our home, which require a neutral wire.
    This switch could be what you need for your specific home, & wiring. It just didnt work for me. It seems to be made well, & is a little shallower depth than the other brand we are using, which is nice if you have shallower depth electrical boxes.
